    <div class="main-wrap">
      <div id="wsite-content" class="wsite-elements wsite-not-footer">
	<div class="wsite-section-wrap">
	<div class="wsite-section wsite-body-section wsite-section-bg-color wsite-background-171" style="background-color: #ffffff;background-image: none;is_customized: 1;" >
		<div class="wsite-section-content">
          <div class="container">
			<div class="wsite-section-elements">
				<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><strong style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0)"><font size="5">DESI</font></strong><strong style="color:rgb(0, 0, 0)"><font size="5">GN 3 2026 - AASTMT&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font size="4">"</font></strong><font size="4"><strong style=""><font color="#2a2a2a">Spiritual Practices and Spaces: Architecture of Meaning and Experience</font></strong><strong style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">"</strong></font></div>

<div class="paragraph" style="text-align:justify;"><font color="#000000"><strong><font size="3">Course Outline:</font></strong></font><br />&#8203;</div>

<div><div id="304647442356723350" align="inherit" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Design 4 Studio</title>
    <style>
        /* Reset and base styles */
        body {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            font-weight: normal;
            -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
            -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
        }

        /* Default text size for desktop - Smaller size */
        .responsive-text {
            font-size: 16px; /* Smaller desktop size */
            font-weight: normal !important;
            color: #000000;
            line-height: 1.4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            text-rendering: optimizeLegibility;
            text-align: left;
            text-align: justify; /* Justified text */
            text-justify: inter-word; /* Better word spacing for justification */
            hyphens: auto; /* Allow hyphenation for better justification */
        }

        /* Mobile-specific adjustments - Smaller size */
        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            .responsive-text {
                font-size: 14px; /* Smaller mobile size */
                font-weight: normal !important;
                line-height: 1.35;
                text-align: justify;
                text-justify: inter-word;
                hyphens: auto;
            }
        }

        /* For very small screens */
        @media (max-width: 480px) {
            .responsive-text {
                font-size: 13px; /* Even smaller for very small screens */
                font-weight: normal !important;
                line-height: 1.3;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p class="responsive-text">
        This course is a continuation of the design stream, but more focused on architectural spatial experience, with projects that are to be oriented towards perceiving architecture as internal spaces which extends to its outer form. The course aims to expose students to experience, visualize, perceive, and learn to create different types of indoor and outdoor spaces, and to gain a deep understanding of the relationship between them. Students are required to create an architectural spatial statement, and explore new ideas, concepts, forms, and thinking methodologies using physical models and digital photo editing. 
<br> <br><br>

Spiritual Practices and Spaces: Architecture of Meaning and Experience
Architecture has the capacity to affect the inner state of the individual, shaping experiences that extend beyond immediate functional needs. In certain spaces, the act of entering differs profoundly from the act of leaving; movement through space becomes a process of psychological and emotional transformation, where pause, reflection, and awareness are encouraged. Such spaces may be described as spiritual—not solely through religious symbolism, but through their ability to foster contemplation, meaning, and inner stillness.
These spaces often emerge from collective values, belief systems, or shared human conditions, expressing a deeper need for purpose and belonging. As human beings seek meaning and reconciliation with their inner lives, architecture has the potential to generate environments that support psychological and spiritual well-being alongside physical use.
This design studio invites students to explore spirituality as an experiential and spatial condition that can be translated into architecture. Rather than approaching spirituality as a fixed religious doctrine, the course examines it as a set of spatial qualities—such as transition, withdrawal, collectivity, and sensory regulation—that can form the foundation of architectural design. Students are encouraged to investigate how architecture can create meditative, reflective, and meaningful environments across a range of contexts, including religious, sacred, and contemporary non-religious settings. Emphasis is placed on articulating these intentions through spatial sequences, material choices, light, sound, and form.


    </p>
</body>
