<div class="paragraph"><font color="#2a2a2a" size="3"><strong>Project Description:</strong><br /><span>&#8203;&#8203;</span></font></div>

<div><div id="382750496521968144" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Design 4 Studio</title>
    <style>
        /* Reset and base styles */
        body {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            font-family: 'Arial', sans-serif;
            font-weight: normal;
            -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
            -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
        }

        /* Default text size for desktop - Smaller size */
        .responsive-text {
            font-size: 16px; /* Smaller desktop size */
            font-weight: normal !important;
            color: #000000;
            line-height: 1.4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            text-rendering: optimizeLegibility;
            text-align: left;
            text-align: justify; /* Justified text */
            text-justify: inter-word; /* Better word spacing for justification */
            hyphens: auto; /* Allow hyphenation for better justification */
        }

        /* Mobile-specific adjustments - Smaller size */
        @media (max-width: 768px) {
            .responsive-text {
                font-size: 14px; /* Smaller mobile size */
                font-weight: normal !important;
                line-height: 1.35;
                text-align: justify;
                text-justify: inter-word;
                hyphens: auto;
            }
        }

        /* For very small screens */
        @media (max-width: 480px) {
            .responsive-text {
                font-size: 13px; /* Even smaller for very small screens */
                font-weight: normal !important;
                line-height: 1.3;
            }
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p class="responsive-text">
        Spiritual architecture refers to spaces concerned with inner states such as reflection, withdrawal, reconciliation, humility, or heightened awareness, regardless of specific religious affiliation. These spaces accommodate a wide spectrum of experiences and architectural typologies, including but not limited to:
<br><br>
A. Withdrawal / Seclusion
Spaces for stepping away from the external world, such as monasteries, or Sufi khilwa spaces or  temples. <br><br>
B. Preparation / Transition
Spaces where individuals undergo spatial and psychological preparation for a significant spiritual moment, such as miqat zones or pilgrimage arrival areas. <br><br>
C. Contemplation / Stillness
Spaces designed to slow down perception and encourage silence, focus, and inward reflection. These can include retreat centers and Zen spaces.<br><br>
D. Collective Spiritual Spaces
Spaces that host shared spiritual or emotional experiences, including gathering, collective stillness, or ritualized presence, such as baptismal complexes and temples. Projects addressing collective spiritual spaces must clearly define the specific collective practice, ritual, or shared condition they are responding to.<br><br>

Students are expected to select one primary spiritual condition and define the intended state change (entering as and exiting as). Based on this, each student will determine an appropriate building typology, which may align with a religious belief system, a secular interpretation, or a personal understanding of spirituality.


<br> <br><br>


    </p>
</body>
</html></div>



</div>

<div class="paragraph"><font color="#2a2a2a" size="3"><strong>Project location:</strong><br /></font><br></div>

<div><div id="319231830266098598" align="left" style="width: 100%; overflow-y: hidden;" class="wcustomhtml"><!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
